column3:
Thank you Hooligan Mag for reviewing #theTTV and interviewing creators Daniel Kyri Madison and Bea Cordelia! 

"Some of the show’s most successful moments come when Jo and Carter encounter obstacles and joy, and the show refuses to look away. Several of these moments revolve around the character’s different experiences with family...The first season certainly stands on its own as a cohesive story"

Congratulations to Rashayla Marie Brown on being named #NewCity’s 2018 Artist of the Moment! In the interview she discusses her art practice in relationship to the art world, including continuing work on her pilot Reality Is Not Good Enough, released on OTV in 2017!

“Writing is always embedded in my practice because there is a lot of writing embedded in performing, at least for me, and making films. It’s not about closing chapters, it’s about making what’s clear to me in my brain clear to other people. I have made a lot of work that refers to popular culture, to a certain kind of specific black, female interiority. And then I made a lot of work that deals with these broad, sweeping historical omissions and also the effects of colonization on the idea of identity. It’s about maintaining a certain specificity of my position and then expanding that to talk about the idea of attachment to identity.”

For the first time ever OTV will be screening in Chicago Parks! We will be at Ping Tom Memorial Park August 30th and September 1st at 9PM screening #theTTV, Code-Switched, Seeds Series and #HairStoryShow! 

Secure your seat for FREE! https://www.eventbrite.com/e/chicago-onscreen-local-film-festival-tickets-48714357956

Thank you Shadow and Act for reviewing Seeds! 

“Seeds aims to be a ‘bold and dynamic narrative that explores their conversations through a hilariously authentic lens,’ and it succeeds in accomplishing that goal. Its cool style and unapologetic tone must be why the series was an Official Selection for the New York TV Festival Independent Pilot Competition, GlowFest and SeriesFest, where the series won Bustle's Best Emerging Female Creator Award. Despite each episode being between five to seven minutes long, the characters are well-rounded individuals who draw you into their world.”

It's #WCW and we're running a $FREE.99 discount for all of our QTWOC to Reunion & OTV Movie Night: Set it Off next week. 

Valid till EOD.

CREATIVE CYPHER is featuring Seeds Series in the first of their two screenings! The Creative Cypher group is a Chicago-based content development group. They focus on accessibility, multiculturism, and diversity in new local web series. Seeds is a socially conscious, comedy web series about four young, black women. Join  Creative Cypher Web Series Showcase 1 - Seeds & Low Strung August 18th, 7:30 p.m. at Chicago Filmmakers!

Don't forget to grab a copy of the Chicago Tribune today! Eli Micky, our head of marketing and "Two Queens in a Kitchen" showrunner is in the food section talking all things #2QIK: Southern Style. 

Read the full article here: http://www.chicagotribune.com/dining/ct-food-2-queens-in-a-kitchen-20180731-story.html

We're expanding our collaboration with Reunion Chicago and screening essential queer films every month! Come through! Proceeds go toward Reunion, one of few consistently intersectional spaces in Chicago.

The Chicago-based content development group CREATIVE CYPHER is screening Seeds Series The group focuses on accessibility, multiculturalism, and diversity in new local web series. Seeds is a socially, conscious, comedy web series that follows four young, black women. Join Creative Cypher Web Series Showcase 1 - Seeds & Low Strung on August 18th, 7:30 p.m. at Chicago Filmmakers!

The Hoodoisie is a revolutionary show locally and beyond! Congrats to Brujos creator Ricardo Gamboa on this in-depth profile on the Chicago Reader. We are proud to co-host livestreams of the political talk show thanks in part to Voqal.

"I'm Mexican-American in a country where Mexican-Americans account for less than 2 percent of all PhD holders," Gamboa [they/them] says. "I'm finishing my doctorate right now, and it is unfair. I could cry right now thinking of all the smart people in my life who are just never going to get there. The obstacles for them to get there are so unfair. When I think about that stuff it's like, because I got access to this specific knowledge in this course, it's not like I got smarter. Part of what I do know is, if I'm one of the 2 percent, it's my job to generalize that knowledge as much as possible."

Cheers to this lovely interview with OTV head of marketing and #2QIK creator Eli Micky in Chicago Tribune Food & Dining! They discuss how Two Queens in a Kitchen started, why we brought E. Patrick Johnson on for season 3’s “Southern Style” and why food is so important to black and queer community. Season 3 premieres this week if you missed it live with SLAY TV!
